googletag.cmd.push(function () {
googletag.display("desktop-article-ad-4");
});
}




Kiambu County Public Health Officer Samuel Mureithi had said he was not aware of the flooding and advised residents to report the matter to the Githurai District Office’s Public Health department. 






A goat chews cud next to garbage dumped next to stagnant raw sewage on February 16, 2021 at Kiuu Estate, Kahawa West.
Photo credit: Kanyiri Wahito | Nation Media Group

 

It is almost two weeks since the flooding, and nothing has been done.  

“They can also go to the local dispensary and report the matter, then I can get details from the facility and be able to do something about the matter. For now, all they need to do is go and report the matter first,” he insists.   

The Kiambu County Government denied opening the dams during heavy rains. 

“Those stories are baseless. They are not true. How can the county be responsible for opening dams when they are, in fact, not in charge of the dams? The dams are managed by the national government and not the county government,” said Mr Francis Wambugu, the Kiambu County communications officer.  



